Or, as is more probable, the work of Manilius was contained in the same volume with one of the Latin versions of Aratus, and the name was carelessly transferred from the poem to which it rightly belonged to a work on the same subject, which itself had been left without a title.

It is not till the xvth century that any MS supplies the name. It is given variously in these as M. Mallius, Manlius, or Manilius. The most important of these MSS, the Vossianus secundus, gives the heading of B. I thus

M Mallii EQOM astronomicon diuo oct qutitrino aug l proemium lib' p‘r. At the end of B. Ι is written Marcii Mallii astronomicon liber primus explicit.
